      "question": "The roots of the quadratic equation $x^2 - 7x + 12 = 0$ are obtained by splitting the middle term. Which of the following is the correct factorised form of the equation?",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "To factorise $x^2 - 7x + 12 = 0$, we look for two numbers whose sum is $-7$ and product is $12$.",
          "The two numbers are $-3$ and $-4$, since $(-3) + (-4) = -7$ and $(-3) \times (-4) = 12$.",
          "Rewrite the middle term: $x^2 - 3x - 4x + 12 = 0$.",
          "Group the terms: $x(x - 3) - 4(x - 3) = 0$.",
          "Factor out the common binomial: $(x - 3)(x - 4) = 0$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$x^2 - 7x + 12 = 0 \\ x^2 - 3x - 4x + 12 = 0 \\ x(x - 3) - 4(x - 3) = 0 \\ (x - 3)(x - 4) = 0$"
      },
      "topic": "Quadratic Equations",
      "subtopic": "factorisation method",
      "marks": 1,
      "type": "mcq",
      "difficulty": "simple",
      "options": [
        "(A) $(x - 3)(x - 4) = 0$",
        "(B) $(x + 3)(x + 4) = 0$",
